"use strict";(self.webpackChunkwebsite=self.webpackChunkwebsite||[]).push([["2845"],{46306:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api","metadata":{"permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api","source":"@site/articles/useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api/index.mdx","title":"useSyncExternalStore - The underrated React API","description":"You might have heard of useSyncExternalStore(), a new React 18 hook to subscribe to external data sources. It is often used internally by state management libraries - like Redux - to implement a selector system.","date":"2022-09-06T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":4.665,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"S\xe9bastien Lorber","title":"Docusaurus maintainer","url":"https://sebastienlorber.com","imageURL":"https://github.com/slorber.png","key":"slorber","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api","title":"useSyncExternalStore - The underrated React API","authors":["slorber"],"date":"2022-09-06T00:00:00.000Z","twitterThreadUrl":"https://slo.im/t/articles/useSyncExternalStore","image":"./social-card.png","isTranslationMissing":true},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Records & Tuples for React","permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/records-and-tuples-for-react"}},"content":"You might have heard of [`useSyncExternalStore()`](https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-reference.html#usesyncexternalstore), a new React 18 hook to **subscribe to external data sources**. It is often used internally by state management libraries - like [Redux](https://github.com/reduxjs/react-redux/pull/1808) - to implement a **selector system**.\\n\\nBut what about using `useSyncExternalStore()` in your own application code?\\n\\nIn this interactive article, I want to present you a problem: **over-returning React hooks triggering useless re-renders**. We will see how `useSyncExternalStore()` can be a good fix.\\n\\n![social card](./social-card.png)\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n<SubscribeFormEmbed />\\n\\nimport {\\n  App,\\n  AppFixed,\\n  ScrollApp,\\n} from \\"@site/articles/useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api/demos\\";\\n\\n## Over-returning hooks\\n\\nLet\'s illustrate the problem with [`useLocation()`](https://reactrouter.com/en/main/hooks/use-location) from React-Router.\\n\\nThis hook returns an object with many attributes (`pathname`, `hash`, `search`...), but you might not read all of them. Just calling the hook will trigger re-renders when any of these attributes is updated.\\n\\nLet\'s consider this app:\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction CurrentPathname() {\\n  const { pathname } = useLocation();\\n  return <div>{pathname}</div>;\\n}\\n\\nfunction CurrentHash() {\\n  const { hash } = useLocation();\\n  return <div>{hash}</div>;\\n}\\n\\nfunction Links() {\\n  return (\\n    <div>\\n      <Link to=\\"#link1\\">#link1</Link>\\n      <Link to=\\"#link2\\">#link2</Link>\\n      <Link to=\\"#link3\\">#link3</Link>\\n    </div>\\n  );\\n}\\n\\nfunction App() {\\n  return (\\n    <div>\\n      <CurrentPathname />\\n      <CurrentHash />\\n      <Links />\\n    </div>\\n  );\\n}\\n```\\n\\n<App />\\n\\nOn any hash link click, the `CurrentPathname` component will re-render, even if it\'s not even using the `hash` attribute \uD83D\uDE05.\\n\\n:::tip\\n\\nWhenever a hook returns data that you don\'t display, think about React re-renders. If you don\'t pay attention, a tiny `useLocation()` call added at the top of a React tree could harm your app\'s performance.\\n\\n:::\\n\\n:::info\\n\\nThe goal is not to criticize React-Router, but rather to illustrate the problem. `useLocation()` is just a good pragmatic candidate to create this interactive article. Your own React hooks and other third-party libraries might also over-return.\\n\\n:::\\n\\n## `useSyncExternalStore` to the rescue?\\n\\nThe [official documentation](https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-reference.html#usesyncexternalstore) says:\\n\\n> useSyncExternalStore is a hook recommended for reading and subscribing from external data sources in a way that\u2019s compatible with concurrent rendering features like selective hydration and time slicing.\\n> This method returns the value of the store and accepts three arguments:\\n>\\n> - `subscribe`: function to register a callback that is called whenever the store changes.\\n> - `getSnapshot`: function that returns the current value of the store.\\n> - `getServerSnapshot`: function that returns the snapshot used during server rendering.\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction useSyncExternalStore<Snapshot>(\\n  subscribe: (onStoreChange: () => void) => () => void,\\n  getSnapshot: () => Snapshot,\\n  getServerSnapshot?: () => Snapshot,\\n): Snapshot;\\n```\\n\\nThis feels a bit abstract. This [beta doc page](https://beta.reactjs.org/learn/you-might-not-need-an-effect#subscribing-to-an-external-store) gives a good example:\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction subscribe(callback) {\\n  window.addEventListener(\\"online\\", callback);\\n  window.addEventListener(\\"offline\\", callback);\\n  return () => {\\n    window.removeEventListener(\\"online\\", callback);\\n    window.removeEventListener(\\"offline\\", callback);\\n  };\\n}\\n\\nfunction useOnlineStatus() {\\n  return useSyncExternalStore(\\n    subscribe,\\n    () => navigator.onLine,\\n    () => true,\\n  );\\n}\\n\\nfunction ChatIndicator() {\\n  const isOnline = useOnlineStatus();\\n  // ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\nIt turns out that the browser history can also be considered as an external data source. Let\'s see how to use `useSyncExternalStore` with React-Router!\\n\\n## Implementing `useHistorySelector()`\\n\\nReact-Router expose everything we need to wire `useSyncExternalStore`:\\n\\n- access the browser history with [`useHistory()`](https://v5.reactrouter.com/web/api/Hooks/usehistory)\\n- subscribe for history updates with [`history.listen(callback)`](https://github.com/remix-run/history/blob/main/docs/api-reference.md#history.listen)\\n- access a snapshot of the current location with [`history.location`](https://github.com/remix-run/history/blob/main/docs/api-reference.md#historylocation)\\n\\n:::caution\\n\\nThis website uses React-Router v5: the solution will be different for React-Router v6 ([see](https://twitter.com/Zh0uzi/status/1567523679604539405)).\\n\\n:::\\n\\nThe implementation of `useHistorySelector()` relatively simple:\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction useHistorySelector(selector) {\\n  const history = useHistory();\\n  return useSyncExternalStore(history.listen, () =>\\n    selector(history),\\n  );\\n}\\n```\\n\\nLet\'s use it in our app:\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction CurrentPathname() {\\n  const pathname = useHistorySelector(\\n    (history) => history.location.pathname,\\n  );\\n  return <div>{pathname}</div>;\\n}\\n\\nfunction CurrentHash() {\\n  const hash = useHistorySelector(\\n    (history) => history.location.hash,\\n  );\\n  return <div>{hash}</div>;\\n}\\n```\\n\\n<AppFixed />\\n\\nNow, when you click on a hash link above, the `CurrentPathname` component will **not re-render** anymore!\\n\\n## Another example: `scrollY`\\n\\nThere are so many external data sources that we can subscribe to, and implementing your own selector system on top might enable you to optimize React re-renders.\\n\\nFor example, let\'s consider we want to use the `scrollY` position of a page. We can implement this custom React hook:\\n\\n```tsx\\n// A memoized constant fn prevents unsubscribe/resubscribe\\n// In practice it is not a big deal\\nfunction subscribe(onStoreChange) {\\n  global.window?.addEventListener(\\"scroll\\", onStoreChange);\\n  return () =>\\n    global.window?.removeEventListener(\\n      \\"scroll\\",\\n      onStoreChange,\\n    );\\n}\\n\\nfunction useScrollY(selector = (id) => id) {\\n  return useSyncExternalStore(\\n    subscribe,\\n    () => selector(global.window?.scrollY),\\n    () => undefined,\\n  );\\n}\\n```\\n\\nWe can now use this hook with an optional selector:\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction ScrollY() {\\n  const scrollY = useScrollY();\\n  return <div>{scrollY}</div>;\\n}\\n\\nfunction ScrollYFloored() {\\n  const to = 100;\\n  const scrollYFloored = useScrollY((y) =>\\n    y ? Math.floor(y / to) * to : undefined,\\n  );\\n  return <div>{scrollYFloored}</div>;\\n}\\n```\\n\\n<ScrollApp />\\n\\nScroll the page and see how the components above re-render? One is re-rendering less than the other!\\n\\n:::info\\n\\nWhen you don\'t need a `scrollY` 1 pixel precision level, returning a wide range value such as `scrollY` can also be considered as over-returning. Consider returning a narrower value.\\n\\nFor example: a `useResponsiveBreakpoint()` hook that only returns a limited set of values (`small`, `medium` or `large`) will be more optimized than a `useViewportWidth()` hook.\\n\\nIf a React component only handles `large` screens differently, you can create an even narrower `useIsLargeScreen()` hook returning a boolean.\\n\\n:::\\n\\n## Conclusion\\n\\nI hope this article convinced you to take a second look at `useSyncExternalStore()`. I feel this hook is currently underused in the React ecosystem, and deserves a bit more attention. There are many external data sources that you can subscribe to.\\n\\nIf you still haven\'t upgraded to React 18, there\'s a npm [use-sync-external-store](https://www.npmjs.com/package/use-sync-external-store) shim that you can already use today in older versions. There is also a `use-sync-external-store/with-selector` export in case you need to return a memoized non-primitive value."},{"id":"records-and-tuples-for-react","metadata":{"permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/records-and-tuples-for-react","source":"@site/articles/old/2020-07-31-records-and-tuples-for-react-developers/index.mdx","title":"Records & Tuples for React","description":".Records & Tuples for React... and how they are much more than immutable data structures.","date":"2020-07-31T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":0.47,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"S\xe9bastien Lorber","title":"Docusaurus maintainer","url":"https://sebastienlorber.com","imageURL":"https://github.com/slorber.png","key":"slorber","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"records-and-tuples-for-react","title":"Records & Tuples for React","description":".Records & Tuples for React... and how they are much more than immutable data structures.","authors":["slorber"],"twitterThreadUrl":"https://slo.im/thread","image":"./images/hero.png","isTranslationMissing":true},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"useSyncExternalStore - The underrated React API","permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api"},"nextItem":{"title":"Using Expo in Gatsby","permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/using-expo-in-gatsby"}},"content":"**Records & Tuples**, a very interesting **[proposal](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-record-tuple)**, has just reached **[stage 2](https://twitter.com/robpalmer2/status/1286040041089904640)** at **TC39**.\\n\\nThey bring **deeply immutable data structures** to JavaScript.\\n\\nBut don\'t overlook their **equality properties**, that are <u>**VERY**</u> interesting for **React**.\\n\\nA whole category of **React bugs** are related to **unstable object identities**:\\n\\n- **Performance**: re-renders that could be avoided\\n- **Behavior**: useless effect re-executions, infinite loops\\n- **API surface**: unability to express when a stable object identity matters\\n\\nI will explain the basics of **Records & Tuples**, and how they can solve **real world React issues**.\\n\\n[![hero](./images/hero.png)](https://sebastienlorber.com/records-and-tuples-for-react)\\n\\n\uD83D\uDD17 [**Read More**](https://sebastienlorber.com/records-and-tuples-for-react)"},{"id":"using-expo-in-gatsby","metadata":{"permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/using-expo-in-gatsby","source":"@site/articles/old/2020-05-11-using-expo-in-gatsby/index.mdx","title":"Using Expo in Gatsby","description":"Using Expo in Gatsby... or how to use cross-platform components in a MDX blog post","date":"2020-05-11T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":0.25,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"S\xe9bastien Lorber","title":"Docusaurus maintainer","url":"https://sebastienlorber.com","imageURL":"https://github.com/slorber.png","key":"slorber","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"using-expo-in-gatsby","title":"Using Expo in Gatsby","description":"Using Expo in Gatsby... or how to use cross-platform components in a MDX blog post","authors":["slorber"],"twitterThreadUrl":"https://slo.im/thread","image":"./images/hero.png","isTranslationMissing":true},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Records & Tuples for React","permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/records-and-tuples-for-react"},"nextItem":{"title":"Atomic CSS-in-JS","permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/atomic-css-in-js"}},"content":"You probably heard of [React-Native-Web](https://github.com/necolas/react-native-web), allowing to render **React-Native views on the web**.\\n\\n**So, what about using React-Native in a Gatsby website?**\\n\\nThis post is a **proof-of-concept**: it contains **React-Native** and **Expo** interactive components, embedded directly into [this article](https://github.com/slorber/sebastienlorber.com/tree/master/content/posts/2020-05-11-using-expo-in-gatsby) (using [MDX](https://github.com/mdx-js/mdx)), of my [open-source](https://github.com/slorber/sebastienlorber.com) Gatsby site.\\n\\n[![hero](./images/hero.png)](https://sebastienlorber.com/using-expo-in-gatsby)\\n\\n\uD83D\uDD17 [**Read More**](https://sebastienlorber.com/using-expo-in-gatsby)"},{"id":"atomic-css-in-js","metadata":{"permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/atomic-css-in-js","source":"@site/articles/old/2020-04-27-atomic-css-in-js/index.mdx","title":"Atomic CSS-in-JS","description":"Atomic CSS-in-JS... or how to scale your CSS-in-JS.","date":"2020-04-27T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":0.46,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"S\xe9bastien Lorber","title":"Docusaurus maintainer","url":"https://sebastienlorber.com","imageURL":"https://github.com/slorber.png","key":"slorber","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"atomic-css-in-js","title":"Atomic CSS-in-JS","description":"Atomic CSS-in-JS... or how to scale your CSS-in-JS.","authors":["slorber"],"twitterThreadUrl":"https://slo.im/thread","image":"./images/hero.png","isTranslationMissing":true},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Using Expo in Gatsby","permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/using-expo-in-gatsby"},"nextItem":{"title":"Handling API request race conditions in React","permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react"}},"content":"With recent production deployments from Facebook and Twitter, I think a new trend is slowly growing: atomic CSS-in-JS.\\n\\nIn this post, we\'ll see what atomic CSS is, how it relates to functional / utility-first CSS like TailwindCSS, and that big players are adopting it in their modern React codebases.\\n\\nAs I\'m not a expert of this subject, don\'t expect a deep dive about the pros and cons. I just hope you get an idea about what it\'s about.\\n\\n**Note**: Atomic CSS is not really related to [Atomic Design](https://atomicdesign.bradfrost.com/).\\n\\n[![hero](./images/hero.png)](https://sebastienlorber.com/atomic-css-in-js)\\n\\n\uD83D\uDD17 [**Read More**](https://sebastienlorber.com/atomic-css-in-js)"},{"id":"handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react","metadata":{"permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react","source":"@site/articles/old/2019-08-30-handling-race-conditions-in-react/index.mdx","title":"Handling API request race conditions in React","description":"Handling API request race conditions in React... or how to avoid rendering the wrong data","date":"2019-08-30T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":0.24,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"S\xe9bastien Lorber","title":"Docusaurus maintainer","url":"https://sebastienlorber.com","imageURL":"https://github.com/slorber.png","key":"slorber","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react","title":"Handling API request race conditions in React","description":"Handling API request race conditions in React... or how to avoid rendering the wrong data","authors":["slorber"],"twitterThreadUrl":"https://slo.im/thread","image":"./images/hero.png","isTranslationMissing":true},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Atomic CSS-in-JS","permalink":"/zh-Hans/articles/atomic-css-in-js"}},"content":"Many blog articles talk about loading api/async data in React apps, with `componentDidMount`, `useEffect`, Redux, Apollo...\\n\\nYet, all those articles are **generally optimistic**, and never mention something important to consider: race conditions could happen, and your UI may end up in an **inconsistent state**.\\n\\n[![hero](./images/hero.png)](https://sebastienlorber.com/handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react)\\n\\n\uD83D\uDD17 [**Read More**](https://sebastienlorber.com/handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react)"}]}}')}}]);